## 5. Technical stack

- **Framework:** React (single-file `.jsx` artifact)
- **Storage:** `window.storage` (artifact persistent storage). **Do NOT use `localStorage` or `sessionStorage`** — they are not supported in this environment and will break the artifact.
- **Charts:** `recharts` (already available)
- **Icons:** `lucide-react` (already available)
- **Styling:** Tailwind core utility classes only (no custom CSS compilation)
- **State:** React hooks (`useState`, `useReducer`, `useEffect`). No external state library needed.

### Required first step

Before writing code, **read** `/mnt/skills/public/frontend-design/SKILL.md`. It contains design tokens, component patterns, and styling constraints specific to this environment. The output should look like a real product, not an AI-generated mock.

---

## 6. Design principles (non-negotiable)

1. **Mobile first.** Assume the user is in a gym, on a phone, with one hand and sweaty fingers. Tap targets must be large. Forms must minimise typing.
2. **Speed of entry > visual richness.** Logging a working set should take ≤3 taps from the active session screen.
3. **No friction on read.** Viewing past sessions and progress charts should be one tap from anywhere.
4. **Quiet by default.** No celebrations, streaks, badges, gamification. The user is an adult tracking their own work. The app is a notebook, not a coach.
5. **Honest data.** Never auto-fill, estimate, or interpolate missing values. Empty is empty.
6. **Offline-capable.** All data lives in `window.storage`. No network calls required for core flows.
7. **No flattery.** Don't tell the user "great job!" Don't add motivational quotes. Yates' system is built on honest self-assessment, not external validation.

---

## 7. Out of scope (do NOT build)

- Multi-user, accounts, login, profiles
- Social features (sharing, feeds, comments, leaderboards)
- Workout generation / "today's workout" suggestions
- Video / image / form-check uploads
- Macro/calorie tracking (diet is logged as free-text notes + tags, that's it)
- Wearable integration / heart-rate sync
- Push notifications
- Pre-built workout programs
- Exercise demonstration videos or animated diagrams
- AI coaching / chat / suggestions beyond the deload and overtraining warnings specified above

If unsure whether a feature belongs, ask: *"Did Yates' physical notebook do this in 1985?"* If no, leave it out.

---

## 8. Acceptance checklist

The build is complete when a user can:

- [ ] Log a complete session (warm-ups + working set to failure + drop set + notes) in under 60 seconds
- [ ] Re-open a draft session and continue where they left off
- [ ] Search for "bench press" and see every time they've done it
- [ ] Open the progression chart for any exercise and see weight × reps over time
- [ ] Mark an experiment ("started 4×/week on March 1") and see it on relevant charts
- [ ] Set a monthly target and mark it achieved
- [ ] See a deload prompt after 6 weeks of consecutive hard training
- [ ] See an overtraining warning after 3 flat sessions in a row
- [ ] See a "trained X twice this week" warning if a non-calf muscle is logged twice within 7 days
- [ ] Use the app entirely offline
- [ ] Close the browser and reopen it and have all data still there

---

## 9. First-run state

The app should boot with sensible defaults:

- Settings: unit = `kg`, deload reminder after 6 weeks, weekly session target = 3
- Empty exercise library (populated as the user types new exercises)
- Friendly empty states on every screen explaining what will appear once data exists

Don't pre-populate sample data, demo workouts, or onboarding tutorials. The user already read the training guide — they know what to do.
